column2: missense mutations at the same amino acid or identical in-frame insertions or deletions) divided by the total number of mutations.  The TSG Score was defined as the number of truncating mutations divided by the total number of mutations.   Truncating mutations included nonsense mutations
column3: insertions or deletions that alter the reading frame
column5: or mutations at the normal stop codon predicted to result in a longer protein.   When a gene had an oncogene score >20% and a TSG Score >5%
column6: it was classified as a TSG because well-studied oncogenes rarely harbor stop codons.     The major data source for this classification was the COSMIC database (www.sanger.ac.uk/genetics/CGP/cosmic/).  To be classified as an oncogene
column7: there had to be >10 clustered mutations in this database.  To be classified as a tumor suppressor gene
column8: there had had to be at least 7 inactivating mutations recorded in this database.     In those cases in which  7  to 20 inactivating mutations  were recorded in the COSMIC database
column9: manual curation was performed.  This curation was used to identify other examples of mutations not yet recorded in the COSMIC database and to exclude the most common artifacts encountered in next-generation sequencing
column10: such as mapping errors and high mutation frequencies  observed in normal tissues.   Genes with mutations occurring predominantly in tumors with very high rates of mutation

column13: the 20/20 rule can be improved by (i)  considering mutations only in particular tumor types
column14: rather than in all tumor types combined (as done here); (ii) requiring a higher number (e.g.
column15: 15) of clustered or inactivating mutations as a threshold for inclusion; and (iii) for genes with thousands of recorded mutations
